00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:04.331
Professor Ben Polak:
Last time we looked at how

00:00:04.331 --> 00:00:07.664
to apply our new idea of
sub-game perfect equilibrium to

00:00:07.664 --> 00:00:11.207
a whole bunch of games,
and our general idea for how to

00:00:11.207 --> 00:00:14.530
solve the sub-game perfect
equilibrium is as follows.

00:00:14.530 --> 00:00:17.705
We looked at each sub-game.
We solved for the Nash

00:00:17.705 --> 00:00:20.858
equilibrium in the sub-game,
that is something we learned to

00:00:20.858 --> 00:00:23.550
do long ago.
And then we rolled back the

00:00:23.550 --> 00:00:26.490
payoffs: we rolled them back up
the tree.

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:29.230
And towards the end we learned
something interesting.

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:32.039
I'm not going to go back to it
today--I just want to emphasize

00:00:32.039 --> 00:00:34.556
it.
We learned that strategic

00:00:34.556 --> 00:00:37.527
effects matter.
So in that investment game we

00:00:37.527 --> 00:00:40.178
looked at last time,
when you're considering whether

00:00:40.178 --> 00:00:42.050
to rent a new piece of
machinery,

00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:46.260
it made a very big difference
whether you considered how this

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.910
action would affect the actions
of the other side;

00:00:49.910 --> 00:00:51.530
in this case,
how it affects your

00:00:51.530 --> 00:00:54.110
competition.
This is a very general idea,

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:57.147
a very general point.
So just to give you a couple of

00:00:57.147 --> 00:00:59.118
more examples,
when you're designing tax

00:00:59.118 --> 00:01:02.101
systems--I mentioned this last
time--when you're designing a

00:01:02.101 --> 00:01:04.306
tax system,
to make some changes in the

00:01:04.306 --> 00:01:05.806
U.S.
tax system, it's not good

00:01:05.806 --> 00:01:09.014
enough to look at how people are
behaving in the old tax system

00:01:09.014 --> 00:01:11.859
and just calculate in an
accounting manner how much more

00:01:11.859 --> 00:01:15.114
money you're going to raise,
or how much money it's going to

00:01:15.114 --> 00:01:17.041
cost you.
You have to take into account

00:01:17.041 --> 00:01:19.510
how that's going to lead to
changes in behavior.

00:01:19.510 --> 00:01:23.596
Once again, that's a strategic
effect, and in the homework that

00:01:23.596 --> 00:01:27.178
you're handing in today,
all of you will have had a nice

00:01:27.178 --> 00:01:29.769
example of that in the toll
booth problem.

00:01:29.769 --> 00:01:32.660
So in the toll booth problem,
when you're putting tolls on

00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:35.748
roads--or more generally,
when you're building new roads,

00:01:35.748 --> 00:01:37.135
new bridges,
new flyovers,

00:01:37.135 --> 00:01:39.463
new bypasses,
you need to take into account

00:01:39.463 --> 00:01:42.656
how those new tolls,
how those new roads will affect

00:01:42.656 --> 00:01:46.052
all of traffic flow.
Traffic flow down the tree will

00:01:46.052 --> 00:01:49.836
form a new equilibrium and you
need to consider that in

00:01:49.836 --> 00:01:53.690
designing your tolls and
designing your road system.

