01:02:30.510 --> 01:02:40.041
Here's our whole game,
we found the pure SPEs but now

01:02:40.041 --> 01:02:46.639
we're ready to find the mixed
SPE.

01:02:46.639 --> 01:02:51.004
The mixed sub-game perfect
equilibrium has Player A--before

01:02:51.004 --> 01:02:54.240
I do that let me just give this
P a name.

01:02:54.240 --> 01:02:57.424
Let me call this P, P*.
So V / [V + C],

01:02:57.424 --> 01:03:01.196
let's call it P*.
So the mixed sub-game perfect

01:03:01.196 --> 01:03:06.379
equilibrium has Player I mixing,
fighting with probability of P*

01:03:06.379 --> 01:03:09.738
in the first stage;
and in the second stage,

01:03:09.738 --> 01:03:12.382
again mixing,
fighting with probability of

01:03:12.382 --> 01:03:18.076
P*.
So this is Player 1 and Player

01:03:18.076 --> 01:03:25.405
2 does exactly the same thing.
While we're here,

01:03:25.405 --> 01:03:31.920
what's the expected payoff for
each player if they're playing

01:03:31.920 --> 01:03:36.590
this mixed sub-game perfect
equilibrium?

01:03:36.590 --> 01:03:47.119
It's 0--the payoff from
this--the expected payoff is 0.

01:03:47.119 --> 01:03:51.533
So now we're actually getting
somewhere, now we're really

01:03:51.533 --> 01:03:55.485
getting somewhere.
So let's just take a deep

01:03:55.485 --> 01:03:59.538
breath and see where we are.
We broke this game down,

01:03:59.538 --> 01:04:02.894
this complicated game we played
in class, that conceivably--for

01:04:02.894 --> 01:04:04.799
example,
when New York is playing New

01:04:04.799 --> 01:04:06.949
Jersey--conceivably it could go
on all night.

01:04:06.949 --> 01:04:08.759
Apparently not when the Texans
are playing each other or the

01:04:08.759 --> 01:04:10.139
football team is playing the
baseball team,

01:04:10.139 --> 01:04:12.468
but when we have New York and
New Jersey it could go on all

01:04:12.468 --> 01:04:14.361
night.
We curtailed it to a two period

01:04:14.361 --> 01:04:16.947
game, but in a minute,
we're going to go back to the

01:04:16.947 --> 01:04:19.563
infinite game.
In this two period game,

01:04:19.563 --> 01:04:24.164
I tried to argue--I'm trying to
convince you--that you could get

01:04:24.164 --> 01:04:28.036
fighting occurring just in
equilibrium with absolutely

01:04:28.036 --> 01:04:32.199
standard rational players:
nothing to do with pride,

01:04:32.199 --> 01:04:34.579
nothing to do with reputation,
nothing to do with the fact

01:04:34.579 --> 01:04:37.126
that these guys are crazy guys
who drunk the water in New York

01:04:37.126 --> 01:04:39.530
and New Jersey,
God help them.

01:04:39.530 --> 01:04:45.039
You can get fighting with
ordinary people in equilibrium.

01:04:45.039 --> 01:04:49.066
What we've shown is the way in
which you can get fighting is in

01:04:49.066 --> 01:04:53.442
a mixed strategy equilibrium.
In each period of the game,

01:04:53.442 --> 01:04:56.329
people fight with probability
P.

01:04:56.329 --> 01:05:00.177
That's just enough fight to
give the other side an incentive

01:05:00.177 --> 01:05:03.567
to quit and just enough
probability of the other side

01:05:03.567 --> 01:05:07.350
quitting to give the other side
an incentive to fight;

01:05:07.350 --> 01:05:10.922
just exactly enough.
If they play that equilibrium

01:05:10.922 --> 01:05:14.686
in every period,
there's some chance of the game

01:05:14.686 --> 01:05:19.016
ending but with probability P,
the game goes forward to the

01:05:19.016 --> 01:05:21.665
next period.
So you could potentially have

01:05:21.665 --> 01:05:24.789
fights for two periods.
By the way, with what

01:05:24.789 --> 01:05:28.699
probability would there be a
fight in both periods?

01:05:28.699 --> 01:05:31.144
That's a good homework
question, I won't answer it

01:05:31.144 --> 01:05:32.940
here, you can work it out at
home.

01:05:32.940 --> 01:05:38.010
Should we do it here?
Anybody want to tell me?

01:05:38.010 --> 01:05:42.010
So okay, with what probability
do we get a fight in the first

01:05:42.010 --> 01:05:43.592
period;
a real fight,

01:05:43.592 --> 01:05:48.078
a fight involving both players?
We need both players to fight,

01:05:48.078 --> 01:05:50.767
each are fighting with
probability of P,

01:05:50.767 --> 01:05:54.560
so the probability of both of
them fighting is what?

01:05:54.560 --> 01:05:57.245
P².
So to get a fight in the first

01:05:57.245 --> 01:05:59.099
period, the probability is
P².

01:05:59.099 --> 01:06:03.470
To get a fight in both periods
is what then?

01:06:03.470 --> 01:06:06.045
P^(4).
But we get a fight with

01:06:06.045 --> 01:06:08.840
probability of P^(4) going
through.

01:06:08.840 --> 01:06:11.945
We get fighting in equilibrium.
Moreover, we get some very

01:06:11.945 --> 01:06:15.329
intuitive things that we already
learned in the Hawk-Dove game.

01:06:15.329 --> 01:06:23.965
The probability of fight--so in
this equilibrium--the

01:06:23.965 --> 01:06:33.099
probability of fights occurring
goes up as V goes up.

01:06:33.099 --> 01:06:36.226
So the prize gets bigger,
you're more likely to see

01:06:36.226 --> 01:06:38.290
fights occur:
that seems right.

01:06:38.290 --> 01:06:46.404
It goes down in C.
So the probability of fights

01:06:46.404 --> 01:06:49.763
occurring goes up in the size of
the prize--that seems

01:06:49.763 --> 01:06:53.250
intuitively right--and down in
the cost of fighting.

01:06:53.250 --> 01:06:57.922
Now, okay, that's reasonable,
but I claimed I could show you

01:06:57.922 --> 01:07:02.989
this not in a two period game,
but in an infinite period game.

01:07:02.989 --> 01:07:06.732
So let me spend the last five
minutes taking us to infinite

01:07:06.732 --> 01:07:10.469
period games.
So everybody take a deep breath.

01:07:10.469 --> 01:07:12.184
We're now going to consider
something, we've never done

01:07:12.184 --> 01:07:14.355
before.
We're going to consider a game

01:07:14.355 --> 01:07:21.139
that could go on forever.
It could go on forever.

