But what I want to show you is

01:08:35.541 --> 01:08:38.092
that we can still solve this
game even though it's an

01:08:38.092 --> 01:08:40.810
infinite period game.
How are we going to do that?

01:08:40.810 --> 01:08:43.409
Let's look at a particular
stage.

01:08:43.409 --> 01:08:49.221
Let's call the stage Stage
4,503 whatever that number was:

01:08:49.221 --> 01:08:54.454
4,503, whatever it was.
So here is the stage,

01:08:54.454 --> 01:09:01.103
this arbitrary stage,
and the tree for this arbitrary

01:09:01.103 --> 01:09:07.345
stage looks like this.
What I'm going to do is:

01:09:07.345 --> 01:09:13.436
this is Stage 4,503,
and what I'm going to add to

01:09:13.436 --> 01:09:19.399
this is that before you get into
this stage,

01:09:19.399 --> 01:09:24.100
you're going to incur sunk
costs.

01:09:24.100 --> 01:09:34.337
If you go on playing after this
stage then you're going to get

01:09:34.337 --> 01:09:39.783
continuation values.
So going into the beginning of

01:09:39.783 --> 01:09:43.290
the game, you've incurred some
sunk costs and if you come out

01:09:43.290 --> 01:09:45.569
on the other side and go on
playing,

01:09:45.569 --> 01:09:48.091
you're going to play some
equilibrium and get continuation

01:09:48.091 --> 01:09:49.953
values.
But otherwise everything else

01:09:49.953 --> 01:09:53.662
is the same.
We still have (0,0) here,

01:09:53.662 --> 01:09:58.912
we still have (0,
V) here, we still have (V,

01:09:58.912 --> 01:10:06.360
0) here and here we still have
-C plus continuation values and

01:10:06.360 --> 01:10:13.384
-C plus continuation values.
This is something we've seen

01:10:13.384 --> 01:10:15.908
before.
This little box is something

01:10:15.908 --> 01:10:18.659
we've seen before.
Essentially we've got sunk

01:10:18.659 --> 01:10:21.149
costs in front,
but they're irrelevant.

01:10:21.149 --> 01:10:23.947
We've got continuation values
at the end but we know how to

01:10:23.947 --> 01:10:26.310
handle them, we just put them
into the payoffs.

01:10:26.310 --> 01:10:31.686
So suppose now that in the
continuation game,

01:10:31.686 --> 01:10:38.039
people play the mixed strategy
that we just found.

01:10:38.039 --> 01:10:42.313
Suppose that in the
continuation game people mixed

01:10:42.313 --> 01:10:46.587
with probability P:
so they fight with P* and quit

01:10:46.587 --> 01:10:50.703
with probability 1 - P*.
Suppose in the continuation

01:10:50.703 --> 01:10:53.119
game they're playing a mixed
strategy.

01:10:53.119 --> 01:10:58.159
In that case,
what is the continuation value

01:10:58.159 --> 01:11:02.020
of the game?
What is it?

01:11:02.020 --> 01:11:04.972
It's 0 right.
If they're mixing in the

01:11:04.972 --> 01:11:10.065
future, they always have the
option to quit so it must be

01:11:10.065 --> 01:11:13.340
that the continuation value is
0.

01:11:13.340 --> 01:11:22.338
So if they mix in the future
then the continuation value is

01:11:22.338 --> 01:11:28.524
(0,0).
So now let's go back to this

01:11:28.524 --> 01:11:31.793
board.
To make this board equivalent

01:11:31.793 --> 01:11:35.369
to the board above,
all I need to do is one thing.

01:11:35.369 --> 01:11:42.090
I need to add on some sunk
costs at the front.

01:11:42.090 --> 01:11:43.880
I've got sunk costs at the
front.

01:11:43.880 --> 01:11:47.720
I'm going to play the game.
And then I'm going to get,

01:11:47.720 --> 01:11:50.960
instead of stage 2 values,
I'm going to get stage--what

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:54.619
was it?--4,503 and all stages in
the future values in here and

01:11:54.619 --> 01:11:57.319
here, but otherwise it's the
same thing.

01:11:57.319 --> 01:12:00.380
And what's convenient is:
all of those are 0 anyway.

01:12:00.380 --> 01:12:04.657
Since they're all 0 anyway,
this matrix is still correct,

01:12:04.657 --> 01:12:08.706
the continuation values are 0
and 0, these are now the

01:12:08.706 --> 01:12:10.540
continuation values.

01:12:17.760 --> 01:12:21.649
And so if I look for a
mixed-strategy equilibrium in

01:12:21.649 --> 01:12:25.310
this game, it's something I've
solved already.

01:12:25.310 --> 01:12:27.690
What's the mixed strategy
equiliibrium in this game?

01:12:27.690 --> 01:12:33.627
Anybody?
It's exactly what we found

01:12:33.627 --> 01:12:36.935
before.
Just as before,

01:12:36.935 --> 01:12:44.920
I'm going to mix with
probability of V / [V + C].

01:12:44.920 --> 01:12:47.725
Let's summarize,
we did something today--just

01:12:47.725 --> 01:12:50.020
now--that we've never done
before.

01:12:50.020 --> 01:12:53.966
We've looked at an infinite or
at least potentially infinite

01:12:53.966 --> 01:12:57.109
period game: a game that could
go on forever.

01:12:57.109 --> 01:13:01.588
The way in which we handled the
game that could go on forever

01:13:01.588 --> 01:13:04.260
was what?
We noticed two things.

01:13:04.260 --> 01:13:07.797
We noticed that part of the
game that comes before,

01:13:07.797 --> 01:13:10.840
that part of the game that's
passed already,

01:13:10.840 --> 01:13:14.590
anything that happened there is
just a sunk cost.

01:13:14.590 --> 01:13:17.840
It's irrelevant.
It hurts if it's a cost.

01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:20.503
It's nice if it's a gain.
But it's sunk,

01:13:20.503 --> 01:13:24.484
you can't affect it now.
Anything in the future can be

01:13:24.484 --> 01:13:28.960
summarized by the value,
the payoff I'm going to get in

01:13:28.960 --> 01:13:33.520
the future by playing the
equilibrium in the future.

01:13:33.520 --> 01:13:37.680
In this case,
the future meant mixing.

01:13:37.680 --> 01:13:42.604
Mixing gave me the value of 0.
So here I am getting 0 from the

01:13:42.604 --> 01:13:45.784
future.
Then I can just analyze the

01:13:45.784 --> 01:13:50.434
game in the stage in which I'm
in, just as if it was an

01:13:50.434 --> 01:13:54.739
ordinary, bog-standard,
simultaneous move game.

01:13:54.739 --> 01:13:56.240
When we did so,
in this particular

01:13:56.240 --> 01:13:58.969
example--we're going to see more
examples like this after the

01:13:58.969 --> 01:14:00.880
break--but in this particular
example,

01:14:00.880 --> 01:14:03.619
we found out something quite
surprising.

01:14:03.619 --> 01:14:07.083
This thing we found out was,
in these war of attrition

01:14:07.083 --> 01:14:10.090
settings, there is an
equilibrium with rational

01:14:10.090 --> 01:14:12.751
players--more than that,
common knowledge of

01:14:12.751 --> 01:14:14.853
rationality: everybody's
rational, everyone knows

01:14:14.853 --> 01:14:17.479
everyone else is rational--there
are equilibria in which,

01:14:17.479 --> 01:14:21.310
not only people fight but they
could fight forever.

01:14:21.310 --> 01:14:25.002
In every period they fight with
some probability and we got an

01:14:25.002 --> 01:14:28.332
extra prediction out of it,
a prediction that we weren't

01:14:28.332 --> 01:14:30.094
expecting.
Let me just give you that

01:14:30.094 --> 01:14:32.069
prediction, and then we'll leave
the class with that.

01:14:32.069 --> 01:14:36.198
The extra prediction is this,
if we look at these wars of

01:14:36.198 --> 01:14:40.696
attrition, and we keep track of
the time in which the--hang on

01:14:40.696 --> 01:14:44.529
guys don't rush to the back
yet--one more thing.

01:14:44.529 --> 01:14:49.678
If we look at the time in which
the games have gone on and keep

01:14:49.678 --> 01:14:54.660
track of the probability that a
war will end at that time.

01:14:54.660 --> 01:14:57.839
So imagine this is World War I.
You could imagine World War I

01:14:57.839 --> 01:14:59.384
going for one year,
or two years,

01:14:59.384 --> 01:15:01.460
or three years,
or 20 years or whatever.

01:15:01.460 --> 01:15:05.782
The probability distribution in
this war of attrition is going

01:15:05.782 --> 01:15:08.632
to look like this.
In every period,

01:15:08.632 --> 01:15:12.930
the probability of continuing
is just P*².

01:15:12.930 --> 01:15:15.271
So, in every period,
the chance that--as you get

01:15:15.271 --> 01:15:18.261
further into the future there's
a greater chance the war will

01:15:18.261 --> 01:15:20.634
end.
You can get very long,

01:15:20.634 --> 01:15:24.020
very costly wars;
that's the bad news.

01:15:24.020 --> 01:15:26.770
The good news is it doesn't
happen very often.

01:15:26.770 --> 01:15:29.553
I guess we're all involved in a
rather large and costly war

01:15:29.553 --> 01:15:32.384
right now, so I'll leave you
with that pleasant thought over

01:15:32.384 --> 01:15:35.046
Thanksgiving.
Have a good break and we'll see

